{"id":"1203.3090","submitter":"Bernard Schutz","authors":"Bernard F. Schutz","title":"Thoughts about a conceptual framework for relativistic gravity","comments":"Talk presented at the conference History of General Relativity 7\n  (HGR7), Canary Islands, 2005","journal-ref":"Einstein and the Changing Worldviews of Physics, Birkhaueser 2012,\n  pp 259-269","doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"physics.hist-ph gr-qc","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  I consider the isolation of general relativity research from the rest of\ntheoretical physics during the 1930s-1950s, and the subsequent reinvigoration\nof the field. I suggest that the main reason for the isolation was that\nrelativists of the time did not develop heuristic concepts about the physics of\nthe theory with which they could communicate with other physicists, and that\nthe revival happened when they began to develop such concepts. A powerful\nheuristic today is the concept of a black hole, which is a robust and stable\ncomponent of many astronomical systems. During the 1930s relativists could only\noffer the \"Schwarzschild singularity\". I argue that the change occurred at\nleast partly because key theoretical physicists schooled in quantum theory\nentered relativity research and began to approach problematic issues by asking\nquestions about observable effects and the outcomes of thought experiments. The\nresult was the development of a physical intuition about such things as black\nholes, which could then be communicated to non-specialists. Only then was it\npossible to integrate general relativity fully into the rest of physics.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 14 Mar 2012 14:05:04 GMT"}],"update_date":"2012-03-15"}
